WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:25.670
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
Good afternoon everyone.

00:00:25.670 --> 00:00:28.250
Welcome. So, nice to see you here.

00:00:29.670 --> 00:00:34.160
if anybody is serious about
Afro Cuban music or Latin Jazz,

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:36.480
then surely you know
the name Machito;

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:43.270
one of the most important band
leaders in American music.

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:50.410
He more or less defines the
genre, especially for this music

00:00:50.410 --> 00:00:55.210
in the 1940s, 50s, 60s, and 70s.

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:57.600
We're going to celebrate his
music and his legacy today.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:00.780
And, I can't think of
anybody better to help us do

00:01:00.780 --> 00:01:05.070
that than the gentleman
sitting at my right.

00:01:05.070 --> 00:01:09.010 position:56%
If you've been following Latin jazz,

00:01:09.010 --> 00:01:12.520
you know him as a world
famous percussionist.

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:13.820
He worked in the studios.

00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:18.540 position:56%
He recorded hundreds maybe thousands
of jingles and commercials.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:20.160
But, I've been seeing
him, most recently,

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:23.380
with Dizzy Gillespie's
Afro Cuban experience.

00:01:23.380 --> 00:01:27.150
In fact, that's when we
first met face to face

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:29.890
after a performance
at the Kennedy Center.

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:34.470
This is Mario Grillo.

00:01:34.470 --> 00:01:37.960 position:56%
And I, and I use that pronunciation.

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:39.260
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Right.

00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:40.560
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Yes.

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:45.370
He took over leadership of the
orchestra after his father died.

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:49.510
And, he's help maintain his legacy.

00:01:49.510 --> 00:01:51.830
Now, we have a special announcement
that we're going to share

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:54.060
with you in a few minutes.

00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:56.780
And, we hope you're going to
stick around for all of that.

00:01:56.780 --> 00:02:00.960
We'll talk a little bit
about his father's music.

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:04.380
And then, we'll open it up for
any questions you might have.

00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:06.780
We also have some clips
to share with you.

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:08.390
So, I think this will be fun.

00:02:08.390 --> 00:02:11.870
This is being videotaped for
webcast, just so you'll know.

00:02:11.870 --> 00:02:17.970
I hope you help me
welcome Mario Grillo.

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:27.250
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Thank
you for having me here.

00:02:27.250 --> 00:02:29.570
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
It's our pleasure.

00:02:29.570 --> 00:02:31.790
Now, as I mentioned,
everybody in this room,

00:02:31.790 --> 00:02:34.030 position:56%
I'm guessing, knows Machito's music.

00:02:34.030 --> 00:02:36.350
Let's see a show of hands.

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:38.690
Oh, good sign.

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:43.420
But, not everybody knows about his
biography, details about his life.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:45.560
And, I want to start off by
talking a little bit about that.

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:47.800
Let's establish some
fact first of all.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:50.680
He was born when and where?

00:02:50.680 --> 00:02:59.040
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Machito was born
December 3rd 1908 in Havana Cuba.

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:03.870
He migrated to New
York City in 1937.

00:03:03.870 --> 00:03:08.900
When he got here, in 1937, he
immediately started working

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:13.710
with what few bands there were
in New York City at that time.

00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:18.260
And, I asked him how he did that
and he said well gigs or, you know,

00:03:18.260 --> 00:03:24.800
dances in those days played, paid
$2, you know, $3 for the night.

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:30.450
So, he would go to these dances
with $10 in his pocket or 20 bucks.

00:03:30.450 --> 00:03:33.990 position:56%
And, he would go up to the singer or
whatever band it was and say listen,

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:36.670
I'll give you a dollar if
you let me sing a tune.

00:03:36.670 --> 00:03:40.370
And, that's how people
started hearing him and knowing

00:03:40.370 --> 00:03:44.880
who is this Machito person.

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:46.420
Shortly thereafter, he got

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:51.250
with an incredible Puerto Rican
band leader named Noro Morales

00:03:51.250 --> 00:03:52.590
and he joined Noro's band.

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:54.350
Then, after that, a dear friend

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:58.710
of his named Miguelito Valdez
was working with Xavier Cugat

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:01.430
and decided to leave
and make his own band.

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:05.680
So, now he goes to Cugat and he
tells him I'm leaving the band

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:10.200
but I got a guy that can
do the job, you know.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:11.890
This guy's dynamite, he can do it.

00:04:11.890 --> 00:04:13.190
He said, but, how can that be?

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:15.650
I'm recording next week.

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:19.660
You know, there's no way he's
going to learn this new material

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:21.510
and everything in a week's time.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:23.640
No way. He said, no,
don't worry about it.

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:25.280
This guy will do it.

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:29.410
and, of the tunes that Noro Morales
picked, he picked one, which is,

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:32.200
which is the standard
called Cachita.

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:38.230
And, that was a block buster hit
sold, I don't know how many copies.

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:43.500
And, from there, you
know, the rest is history.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:47.990
He went to work with
a band Alberto Iznaga.

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:51.040
And, Estrellas Habaneras.

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:56.170 position:56%
And, like all musicians do, and we
still do it today, you pirate a band

00:04:56.170 --> 00:04:58.200
out of the band that you're in.

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:00.720
So then, he took the bass
player, the piano player,

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:02.440
the trumpet player,
the sax, you know,

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:06.480
he took like the entire
band and made his own band.

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:12.670
And, his first arranger was
Jose Madera Sr., Pin Madera.

00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:16.680
He had his own band in 39.

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:20.350
But then, in 1940, my beloved uncle

00:05:20.350 --> 00:05:25.160
and namesake Mario Bauza was
musical director with Chick Webb,

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:32.180
he had gone with Cab Calloway,
Noble Sissel, the Missourians,

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:33.660
all these kind of crazy stuff.

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:36.170
And, he tells my father,
you know, Machito,

00:05:36.170 --> 00:05:37.730
I want to stay in New York, man.

00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:39.730
I don't, I don't want
to keep traveling.

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:43.900
You know, I want to be
in this city permanently.

00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:48.410
And, they reorganized
the orchestra again.

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:51.520
Well, when Mario came to the
band, he came with this idea

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:57.250
and this concept of
taking a big band concept,

00:05:57.250 --> 00:06:01.190
a big band jazz concept
but put a Latin rhythm,

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:04.040
and Afro Cuban rhythm
section underneath it.

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:08.350
From there came things like
tanga, later on Dizzy Gillespie

00:06:08.350 --> 00:06:11.450
which [inaudible] Monteca.

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:13.420 position:56%
These were the ground breaking tunes

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:18.520
which established what then they
called the Cubop period along bop

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:20.090
and bebop period.

00:06:20.090 --> 00:06:25.910
I would say that 95% of the work
that Machito did was in jazz clubs,

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:30.620
you know, like the Birdland and
the Royal Goose and Bop City,

00:06:30.620 --> 00:06:32.520
different places like that.

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:36.060
He did do the Latin scene,
so to speak, Chateau Madrid

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:38.260
and things along those lines.

00:06:38.260 --> 00:06:43.450
But, it always tended to be
more of a jazz side to the band.

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:45.740
Mr. Appelbaum was asking
me, and I was telling him

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:48.670
about this whole thing about
Machito and these Afro Cubans.

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:51.520
Okay, people would ask him
Machito who are your Afro Cubans?

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:55.380
He goes okay, you know, Mark
Freedman, Ken Hitchcock, you know,

00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:59.320
Leslie, I mean, his thing was
he didn't need Afro Cubans.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:01.860
What he needed was musician,

00:07:01.860 --> 00:07:04.080
guys who came with that
big band experience.

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:06.940
Many of the guys that
came to our band had come

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:10.250 position:56%
out of Duke Ellington's and Woody
Herman's band and Buddy Rich's band,

00:07:10.250 --> 00:07:11.950
Thad Jones Mel Lewis Orchestra.

00:07:11.950 --> 00:07:15.030
So, they already came prepared.

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:19.920
The only thing that was always
difficult was to find that clave,

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:22.350
to be able to connect
with that clave.

00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:24.400
But, a couple of challenges
very easy.

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:25.980
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Can
I just ask you quickly,

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:28.250
for anybody watching this webcast?

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:29.550
What is clave.

00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:32.270
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: What clave is a
two-part phrase, four-part phrase,

00:07:32.270 --> 00:07:34.390
you know, it can either
be three two or two three.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:36.190
So, it can be.

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:41.570
[ Singing notes ]

00:07:41.570 --> 00:07:43.510
Or you can reverse it to.

00:07:43.510 --> 00:07:49.070
[ Singing notes ]

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:52.770
That's where you get the
prescription from dancers who say

00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:57.120
that they dance on two, you
know, and it's because of the way

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:00.730
that the clave falls in
that rhythmic patter.

00:08:00.730 --> 00:08:03.680 position:56%
But, I was telling [inaudible] that,
you know, clave isn't everything.

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:05.510
You know, Beethoven's
5th is in clave.

00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:16.620
[ Singing notes ]

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:18.570
That's in clave.

00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:23.400
So, it's, nothing new.

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:26.340
But, it certainly is the
core of what we play.

00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:28.650
It's a very clave driven music.

00:08:28.650 --> 00:08:31.520
I can't play out of clave.

00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:32.820
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
It's the heartbeat.

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:34.120
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: It's the heart.

00:08:34.120 --> 00:08:35.420
It's the pulse.

00:08:35.420 --> 00:08:39.150
And, I have found that
I, I've given up.

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:43.660
I can't. I just, I'll just
like bluff around when

00:08:43.660 --> 00:08:46.510
that jump comes, you know, so.

00:08:46.510 --> 00:08:50.040
[ Singing notes ]

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:55.120
And I'll come, I'll come right
back in again because it's just,

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:59.120 position:56%
I really can't play on a clave, not.

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:03.170
Well, funny thing, working
with Dizzy Gillespie band,

00:09:03.170 --> 00:09:07.540
and more of the jazz format,
the clave is very flexible.

00:09:07.540 --> 00:09:11.290
You know, you can go back and
forth in the middle of a tune.

00:09:11.290 --> 00:09:13.480
I find it tough to do.

00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:17.470
It's cool because I, now I look for
it, you know, I'm conscious of it

00:09:17.470 --> 00:09:19.400
and I know when that
jump is going to come.

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:24.930
But, initially, no, I found
it quite difficult to do.

00:09:24.930 --> 00:09:28.170
But, it's just what's within you.

00:09:28.170 --> 00:09:29.470
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Two quickies.

00:09:29.470 --> 00:09:31.940
Did people call him, as
friends, did they call him Macho?

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:33.240
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Macho.

00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:34.540
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Okay.

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:35.840
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yeah.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:37.140
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
Nobody called him Frank?

00:09:37.140 --> 00:09:38.440
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: No.

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:39.740
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Or Francesco?

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:41.040
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: And,
strangely enough, in our family,

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:42.340
we have some here,
everybody's Frank.

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:46.990
My brother's Frank, his son is
Frank, my daughter's Francesca,

00:09:46.990 --> 00:09:49.910
my brother-in-law is
Frank, his son is Frank.

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:56.000
We have another twin Frank that
we call cockeyed Frank, big Frank,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.360
we have Baby Frank, who is Frank
Serrica [assumed spelling],

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:01.890
we have the other Frank
Hartman, whatever.

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:05.600
So, when you say Frank, in our
house, that, everybody's like,

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:08.750
you know, because there's like
seven, eight, or nine of them.

00:10:08.750 --> 00:10:12.320
But, they know who they are by the
tone of your voice, you know, like,

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:17.700
we always like go Frank
Serrica, the baby, we always used

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:22.220 position:56%
to call him Frank the Greek because,
for his first couple of years,

00:10:22.220 --> 00:10:25.520
[inaudible], you know, we didn't
know what the heck he was saying.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.620
But, yeah, there's a
whole bunch of Franks.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:33.800
But, no, Macho, I would think
everybody just called him Macho.

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:35.100
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
Speaker of family,

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:36.650
when did he meet your mother Hilda?

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:39.390
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: He met
my mother about 1940.

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:40.940
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
And how did they meet?

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:46.700
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: He, well, now
they call them stalkers, in that,

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:48.700
in those days it was a
little different, you know.

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:57.170
He saw this beautiful
girl go by, that was it.

00:10:58.890 --> 00:11:00.750
There's five of us.

00:11:00.750 --> 00:11:02.280
They were pretty busy.

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:12.600
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: And you, in
order of five, which are you?

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:13.900
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Next to last.

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:22.160
It's my sister Martha, my
brother Frank, Barbara, me,

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:27.000
and my little sister Paula.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:28.300
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Paula.

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:29.600
She's a singer.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:30.900
Yeah?

00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:32.200
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yes.

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:33.500
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
She sang with a band.

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:36.910
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: I threw
her out of the band.

00:11:36.910 --> 00:11:40.370
She came to me one day
and asked for a raise.

00:11:40.370 --> 00:11:45.580
And, I didn't think
that was a good idea.

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:48.320
But, she is quite fantastic.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:50.880
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Now, you are
a percussionist, as I mentioned.

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:56.670
Did you study your father's music
or was it just around the house?

00:11:56.670 --> 00:12:01.310
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: You
know what, it's very sad.

00:12:01.310 --> 00:12:11.550
We didn't listen to daddy's music.

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:15.560
Why? Here's a guy walking around
in his underwear every day,

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:17.420
I mean, you know.

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:22.590
He didn't impress us.

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:30.620
So, we, we didn't know,
we didn't know who he was.

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:34.880
But, tremendous person.

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:37.430
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: So, you
know, you grew up with this man.

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:40.910
The world knows him for
his musical contributions.

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:42.210
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yeah.

00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:45.490
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: He's a very
important figure around the world.

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:47.790
And yet, for you, he's
daddy, you know.

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:49.790
So, at what point did you realize?

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:51.090
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Never.

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:52.390
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Who he was?

00:12:52.390 --> 00:12:54.580
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: We still don't.

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:58.040
No clue.

00:12:58.040 --> 00:12:59.340
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: And yet,

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.880
all the musicians you work
with, they all revere him.

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:03.180
Yes?

00:13:03.180 --> 00:13:06.030
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Well,
because he was a very simple

00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:09.340
and very approachable individual.

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:19.100
He believed that there should be
no dead chairs in an orchestra.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:24.280
Meaning, traditionally, it's always
the tenor sax that plays the solos.

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:27.660
It's the third trumpet that
always plays the solos.

00:13:27.660 --> 00:13:29.830
Now, he would turn around
and point to anybody.

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:33.870
And, I asked him one day,
I said why do you do that?

00:13:33.870 --> 00:13:36.510
You know, why does
everybody get to play?

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:40.530
You know, they're supposed be
soloists in a band, not everybody.

00:13:40.530 --> 00:13:44.920 position:56%
He goes no, because if this, if this
band knows that I'm going to turn

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:49.450
around an point to
them to come up front,

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:51.920
they're going to practice
their instrument,

00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:54.940
they're going to send their
suit to the drycleaner,

00:13:54.940 --> 00:14:00.840 position:56%
they're going to polish their shoes,
they're going to iron they're shirt,

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:03.010
and they're going to be
looking for the opportunity

00:14:03.010 --> 00:14:05.630
when they know they
can come out front

00:14:05.630 --> 00:14:09.970
and let people know
what they can do.

00:14:09.970 --> 00:14:16.020
So, I don't want no dead chairs
in my band everybody plays.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:18.310
I do it too.

00:14:18.310 --> 00:14:22.900
I had one guy come in from
Ray Charles orchestra,

00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:24.200
tremendous saxophonist.

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:28.220
So, in the middle of a turn, you
know, so I turned around I pointed

00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:31.900
to him get up there, he
didn't get up, you know.

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:39.030
Now, I'm playing, you know, I turn
around, he didn't get up, you know.

00:14:39.030 --> 00:14:41.750
