00:31:58.040 --> 00:32:04.910
out to all different high security
prisons across the country.

00:32:04.910 --> 00:32:09.280
So now they requested,
you know, music,

00:32:09.280 --> 00:32:14.750
so then they call Machito
Orchestra so we can go to the jail,

00:32:14.750 --> 00:32:18.630
[inaudible], and we hear people,
hey, Machito, 321, hey, Machito,

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:22.650
556, hey, when they open up the
curtain it was all our friends.

00:32:22.650 --> 00:32:23.950
They were all locked up.

00:32:23.950 --> 00:32:27.270
They were being shipped out,
Texas, Leavenworth, you know.

00:32:27.270 --> 00:32:40.020
We have some people here that
spent a little time in Leavenworth,

00:32:40.020 --> 00:32:43.070
on the good side of Leavenworth.

00:32:43.070 --> 00:32:44.370
Yeah, right?

00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:45.670
You guys were in Leavenworth,
weren't you?

00:32:45.670 --> 00:32:50.060
Yeah. So yeah, he always
thought that, so then we played,

00:32:50.060 --> 00:32:52.990
and then the funniest thing was
that, now we're leaving, you know,

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:56.280
the gig is over and we're leaving,
you know, and one of the guys said,

00:32:56.280 --> 00:32:59.900
yo listen man, can I
have those maracas?

00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:02.520
So I'm like, yeah, so now
he's walking out with the band

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:04.330
like he's part of the band
with them, and so like one

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:08.530
of the security guards grabs
him and yanks him back.

00:33:08.530 --> 00:33:10.830
You know, crazy stuff.

00:33:10.830 --> 00:33:15.440
One thing I want to
touch on, maracas.

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:17.900
Maracas was Machito's instrument.

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:19.230
You know? Whatever.

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:22.990 position:56%
So now they would always steal them.

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:25.260
They would always steal them.

00:33:25.260 --> 00:33:28.050 position:56%
They would always steal his maracas.

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:32.140
No matter where he hid them, in
the piano, behind the bandstand,

00:33:32.140 --> 00:33:34.410
no matter what, they'd
find, they'd steal them.

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:37.340
So then we go to Europe, and
we were going to be out man,

00:33:37.340 --> 00:33:39.620
like 10 weeks man,
that's a long time.

00:33:39.620 --> 00:33:43.500
So I took his pair, wouldn't
you know, second gig,

00:33:43.500 --> 00:33:45.460
third gig, they steal them.

00:33:45.460 --> 00:33:48.100 position:56%
Now he's furious, where' my maracas.

00:33:48.100 --> 00:33:51.000
I said don't worry about the
maracas, we're in Berlin,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.300
there's got to be a music store.

00:33:52.300 --> 00:33:56.840
When I went in, there's two
pairs left, so I said to him.

00:33:56.840 --> 00:33:58.140
I said, you know what?

00:33:58.140 --> 00:34:03.030
I should get the two
pair just in case.

00:34:03.030 --> 00:34:05.890
Give him his maracas,
we did a whole bunch

00:34:05.890 --> 00:34:09.000
of gigs, they steal the maracas.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:15.660
So now he comes to me, I
got another pair for you.

00:34:15.660 --> 00:34:16.960
Here, here you go.

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:18.930
And this is your model.

00:34:18.930 --> 00:34:22.120 position:56%
When Latin percussion made the mold,

00:34:22.120 --> 00:34:26.460
that's Machito's mold,
his favorite design.

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:29.910
Anyway, they sold about
80 million pair of those,

00:34:29.910 --> 00:34:32.430
haven't seen a penny,
but that's cool.

00:34:32.430 --> 00:34:40.940
So now, next city I go in, I
bought five pair of maracas,

00:34:40.940 --> 00:34:44.140
and I sold one pair, which I'm sure
you've seen those old traditional

00:34:44.140 --> 00:34:47.150
maracas with the coconuts
painted on them

00:34:47.150 --> 00:34:49.720
and palm trees, you
know, real corny.

00:34:49.720 --> 00:34:52.830
You know? Well, he went
through the other five pair

00:34:52.830 --> 00:34:54.130
in the span of the trip.

00:34:54.130 --> 00:34:56.610
Now we're down to the
last week of the trip.

00:34:56.610 --> 00:34:57.910
No maracas.

00:34:57.910 --> 00:34:59.210
I'm like oh, man.

00:34:59.210 --> 00:35:00.510
I said, well, you know what,

00:35:00.510 --> 00:35:03.140
I've got that bluff pair
that's more decoration

00:35:03.140 --> 00:35:05.200
than anything else, you know?

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:08.050
But now, as I'm ready, I'm going
to give it to him, I'm saying,

00:35:08.050 --> 00:35:11.230
he's going to freak out when
I give him this, you know,

00:35:11.230 --> 00:35:12.910
I mean, what is he going to say?

00:35:12.910 --> 00:35:17.090
You know? So I go into the gig, and
I say, you know what, I'm sorry,

00:35:17.090 --> 00:35:18.390
but this is what I've got.

00:35:18.390 --> 00:35:20.510
And he looks at him
and he goes, wow,

00:35:20.510 --> 00:35:22.570
these are the best maracas
I've ever seen in my life.

00:35:22.570 --> 00:35:25.010
And I'm like, really?

00:35:25.010 --> 00:35:28.530
And he goes those are the
ones I'm going to use today.

00:35:28.530 --> 00:35:33.580
So then, as much as he concerns
himself about a lot of things,

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:37.040
he was really big into his maracas.

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:45.050
As a matter of fact, my
mother, well, let's just say

00:35:45.050 --> 00:35:50.240
that maracas is a very
important story.

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:56.150
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Yeah,
he could really play, too.

00:35:56.150 --> 00:35:58.620
I mean a lot of people, a lot
of singers stand up in front

00:35:58.620 --> 00:36:02.040
of the band and they just sort
of play a few little patterns,

00:36:02.040 --> 00:36:04.080
Machito could really
play those things.

00:36:04.080 --> 00:36:05.380
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yeah.

00:36:05.380 --> 00:36:06.680
Yeah.

00:36:06.680 --> 00:36:13.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Did he teach you
anything about how to play maracas?

00:36:13.270 --> 00:36:17.930
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Well,
one day Daddy tells me,

00:36:17.930 --> 00:36:21.610
I'm sending you two a jingle, with
Chico to help to cover for me.

00:36:21.610 --> 00:36:23.970
I said, okay, cool,
what am I playing?

00:36:23.970 --> 00:36:27.290 position:56%
He said, you're playing the maracas.

00:36:27.290 --> 00:36:31.950
So I looked at him, and I must have
been about, around that time, 15,

00:36:31.950 --> 00:36:36.150 position:56%
16, and I said, you know what,
Daddy, strangely enough if I, Jesus,

00:36:36.150 --> 00:36:37.950
I don't know how to
play the maracas.

00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:40.730
He goes, what do you mean you
don't know how to play the maracas?

00:36:40.730 --> 00:36:42.030
What are you, kidding me?

00:36:42.030 --> 00:36:43.330
You're my son.

00:36:43.330 --> 00:36:44.630
You don't know to play the maracas?

00:36:44.630 --> 00:36:49.500
I said, Daddy, I don't, you
never taught me, I don't know.

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:52.310
He goes, all right, go get
a couple of pair of maracas.

00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:55.080
So I go to the music room,
living room, come back.

00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:59.470
So he stands in front of me, so
now he's standing in front of me,

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:01.570
showing me the motions, you know?

00:37:01.570 --> 00:37:04.640
I couldn't get it, you know?

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:07.310
Now we're standing
side by side looking

00:37:07.310 --> 00:37:10.810
in the mirror, couldn't get it.

00:37:10.810 --> 00:37:16.030 position:56%
You know? So now he's at his wit's
end, you know, he says to me, Jesus,

00:37:16.030 --> 00:37:20.380 position:56%
[inaudible] I can't believe that you
know, you can't play the maracas.

00:37:20.380 --> 00:37:22.250
You're not my son.

00:37:22.250 --> 00:37:24.790
I'm like yo, man, you know?

00:37:24.790 --> 00:37:27.610
So now he gets, he
says, wait a minute,

00:37:27.610 --> 00:37:34.780
so now he stood behind me
and he helped, you know?

00:37:34.780 --> 00:37:37.780
So I'm like, oh, okay, cool.

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:40.720
You know? So now I
go to the recording,

00:37:40.720 --> 00:37:43.260
whatever the case might
be, so I come home,

00:37:43.260 --> 00:37:45.220
and he says to me how did you do?

00:37:45.220 --> 00:37:46.520
I said, well, it was fine man.

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:47.820
It was great.

00:37:47.820 --> 00:37:49.120
He said, did you play the
maracas the way I taught you.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:51.170
I said, yeah, I said,
as a matter of fact,

00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:53.480
Chico O'Farill told me I
play better maracas than you.

00:37:53.480 --> 00:37:57.430
What? Yeah.

00:37:57.430 --> 00:38:01.130
It's a tremendous instrument,
and again,

00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:04.470
there are unique patterns
that you can use.

00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:06.530
But his pattern was very slick,

00:38:06.530 --> 00:38:10.430
and his whole thing
was I use this pattern

00:38:10.430 --> 00:38:14.410
because I don't want my
jacket to get wrinkled.

00:38:14.410 --> 00:38:18.140
You know, many maraca players
keep the maracas tight,

00:38:18.140 --> 00:38:21.780
so then when you let go your
jacket is all, you know,

00:38:21.780 --> 00:38:23.500
it looks like an according.

00:38:23.500 --> 00:38:27.360
But his motion was more out,
so therefore his jacket,

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:29.300
and the crease, would stay as is.

00:38:29.300 --> 00:38:30.600
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Nice.

00:38:30.600 --> 00:38:31.900
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yeah.

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:35.920
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: So, for a
period of a good 20, 25 years, he,

00:38:35.920 --> 00:38:38.130
along with [inaudible],
they're at the top.

00:38:38.130 --> 00:38:42.640
They're at the summit of
Latin music in New York.

00:38:42.640 --> 00:38:47.120
And then by the time the 1960s,
especially the mid and late 60s,

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:49.670
rolled around, tastes
are starting to change.

00:38:49.670 --> 00:38:50.970
There's a new generation.

00:38:50.970 --> 00:38:54.460 position:56%
Yeah. They're not so much interested
in the classic stuff as much

00:38:54.460 --> 00:38:57.890
as they want the new dance
rhythms, they want pachanga,

00:38:57.890 --> 00:39:00.330
they want Latin soul,
they want boogaloo.

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:01.630
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Boogaloo.

00:39:01.630 --> 00:39:02.930
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Yeah.

00:39:02.930 --> 00:39:05.530
So how did Machito adapt, or
did, how well did it adapt?

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:07.040
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Machito's
philosophy was

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:12.540
if you can't beat them, join them.

00:39:12.540 --> 00:39:14.010
My uncle Mario, no.

00:39:14.010 --> 00:39:18.710
Mario was very hard
core on what he wanted.

00:39:18.710 --> 00:39:21.130
Very tough twist his arm.

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:22.430
But Daddy, no.

00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:26.540
His thing was we were
his sounding board.

00:39:26.540 --> 00:39:29.270
We never let, you know,
we never listened

00:39:29.270 --> 00:39:32.060
to Machito's records in my house.

00:39:32.060 --> 00:39:36.250
We don't have record collections.

00:39:36.250 --> 00:39:39.970
But if you want to find the
most complete record collection

00:39:39.970 --> 00:39:43.980
of Machito, go to Our Lady Queen
of Angels Grammar School on 112,

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:48.720
between Second and Third, and
the nuns have all those records.

00:39:48.720 --> 00:39:53.250 position:56%
Because Daddy would come home with a
box of 25 albums and give them out.

00:39:53.250 --> 00:39:57.930
The butcher, the dry cleaner,
Solento's, you know, all the places

00:39:57.930 --> 00:40:00.250
that he stopped, he'd give
them these record albums.

00:40:00.250 --> 00:40:01.550
We never kept them.

00:40:01.550 --> 00:40:03.090
You know, we'd give them away.

00:40:03.090 --> 00:40:09.630
As a matter of fact, one winter
we were all out, you know,

00:40:09.630 --> 00:40:15.600
we were all leaving, we all had
our cars, and so it had snowed,

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:18.880
so it was ice all over
the windshields.

00:40:18.880 --> 00:40:22.210
So my brother and my sisters, they
opened up the trunks and they took

00:40:22.210 --> 00:40:26.740
out Daddy's albums, broke
them in half and used

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:32.010
that to scrape the ice off
the windshield, you know.

00:40:32.010 --> 00:40:34.650
We use to use those albums
to keep the windows open

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:37.730
in the summer to get fresh air.

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:42.750
You see? So now here comes
Daddy and he sees us, you know?

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:48.970
Now when we looked at him our
initial thing was like, oh man.

00:40:48.970 --> 00:40:52.170
He's going to freak out, you know?

00:40:52.170 --> 00:40:53.470
With this?

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:55.490 position:56%
I mean, look, look what we're doing.

00:40:55.490 --> 00:40:57.420
You know? And he looked
at us and he goes,

00:40:57.420 --> 00:41:00.250
listen, give me that other half.

00:41:00.250 --> 00:41:07.910
And he was scraping the ice off the
windshield with his own records.

00:41:07.910 --> 00:41:11.920
These things didn't mean, later
on, they did, like when we would go

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:16.550 position:56%
to Europe, he would go to the record
stores and buy his own albums.

00:41:16.550 --> 00:41:17.890
And I would say Daddy, what are,

00:41:17.890 --> 00:41:20.300
what are you buying
your own albums for?

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:23.410
He goes, it was such a long
time ago, I forgot what's on it.

00:41:23.410 --> 00:41:25.580
I'd like to hear it again.

00:41:25.580 --> 00:41:31.860 position:56%
You know? I mean, we, we, we
weren't collectors of Daddy's stuff.

00:41:31.860 --> 00:41:33.160
Not at all.

00:41:33.160 --> 00:41:35.190 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Do you think he,
do you think he got his royalties?

00:41:35.190 --> 00:41:36.490
Did he ever get exploited?

00:41:36.490 --> 00:41:37.790
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yeah.

00:41:37.790 --> 00:41:39.090
Sure, sure, sure.

00:41:39.090 --> 00:41:43.030 position:56%
Well, what we discovered with all
these world searches, we didn't know

00:41:43.030 --> 00:41:47.700
that Machito sold records in the
Soviet Union, and in Italy, France,

00:41:47.700 --> 00:41:51.680
Germany, Holland, Belgium,
Sweden, Switzerland,

00:41:51.680 --> 00:41:55.770 position:56%
Luxembourg, I mean, Spain, Portugal.

00:41:55.770 --> 00:42:01.080
We had no clue that he had record
sales in all those countries.

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:04.670
Then we did start getting a
lot of royalties back and that,

00:42:04.670 --> 00:42:06.970
and that was a very positive thing.

00:42:06.970 --> 00:42:08.270
We still do.

00:42:08.270 --> 00:42:16.430 position:56%
When they turned over all the albums
to CD's, we did very nicely on that.

00:42:16.430 --> 00:42:21.710
So then, yeah, we certainly
have seen royalties, and we do.

00:42:21.710 --> 00:42:24.680
I mean, it's not like Micahel
Jackson royalties or anything

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:27.220
like that, but certainly,
yes, we do.

00:42:27.220 --> 00:42:28.520
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Okay.

00:42:28.520 --> 00:42:31.700
So back to this period, this
transition period, where he starts

00:42:31.700 --> 00:42:38.090
to adapt the art, changing taste,
and then as so inevitably happens,

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:42.000
the phone doesn't ring
as often for gigs.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:44.670
And I know when we were
talking a few months ago,

00:42:44.670 --> 00:42:49.300
you were telling me how important
Dizzy Gillespie at that time,

00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:51.790
at that period in his career.

00:42:51.790 --> 00:42:53.430
Why don't you tell us a
little bit more about that?

00:42:53.430 --> 00:42:56.950
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Well, the first
thing is that the relationship

00:42:56.950 --> 00:43:00.560
with Machito and Dizzy
was from way, way back.

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:05.210
He was Mario Bauza's room mate when
they were in Cab Calloway's band,

00:43:05.210 --> 00:43:07.750
so the friendship was
a very long one.

00:43:07.750 --> 00:43:12.350
And Dizzy saw that we, we
were having a little bit

00:43:12.350 --> 00:43:16.170
of a tough time there booking big
bands, because big bands was out.

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:17.940
You know, the era was over.

00:43:17.940 --> 00:43:22.360 position:56%
And even Dizzy, himself, had a tough
time booking his full orchestra.

00:43:22.360 --> 00:43:27.450
So then, what he did, was he made
us his accompanying orchestra,

00:43:27.450 --> 00:43:29.990
which took the pressure off
of him an the responsibility

00:43:29.990 --> 00:43:32.840
of running the band, but
knowing that he had a band

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:35.070
that would play whatever
needed to be played.

00:43:35.070 --> 00:43:37.420
And strangely enough,
when Dizzy worked with us,

00:43:37.420 --> 00:43:40.840
he didn't play his
music, he played ours.

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:42.950
We didn't play Monteca
or [inaudible],

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:44.960
we never played any of that.

00:43:44.960 --> 00:43:49.010
We used to play straight ahead
Machito music and Dizzy would blow

00:43:49.010 --> 00:43:52.760
on top of that, which
was incredible.

00:43:52.760 --> 00:44:00.150
And as I had told you,
Dizzy, Dizzy brought back

00:44:00.150 --> 00:44:08.730
to life Machito Orchestra in a
huge way and gave me credibility.

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:12.590
When my dad passed
away, that was it.

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:14.530
we were done.

00:44:14.530 --> 00:44:17.600
You know? That's the end of Machito
Orchestra, forget about these guys.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:20.260
This is finished, you know?

00:44:20.260 --> 00:44:26.530
And I was home six months,
phone never rang, six months.

00:44:26.530 --> 00:44:29.200
And I was like yo, you know?

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:32.780
You know, I'd pick up the phone,
nnnnn, see if it was working.

00:44:32.780 --> 00:44:36.720
You know? And Dizzy
Gillespie calls me.

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:39.330
He tells me, yo Mario,
man, what you doing, man?

00:44:39.330 --> 00:44:45.150
I said, Jesus, dude,
I'm not doing nothing.

00:44:45.150 --> 00:44:48.790
He says, okay, they're going to
call you from the Village Gate

00:44:48.790 --> 00:44:53.010
in New York City, Jack Hook
and Ralph Mercado, these guys,

00:44:53.010 --> 00:44:55.720
they're going to call you up
and they're going to tell you

00:44:55.720 --> 00:45:00.580
that they want you to accompany
me at the Village Gate.

00:45:00.580 --> 00:45:06.370 position:56%
They don't want you to accompany me
at the Village Gate, but I told them

00:45:06.370 --> 00:45:11.420
that I'll only do the Village
Gate if you accompany me.

00:45:11.420 --> 00:45:13.620
You ready?

00:45:13.620 --> 00:45:14.920
I said, yeah.

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:18.650
He said, all right,
they're going to call you.

00:45:18.650 --> 00:45:19.950
I said, okay, cool.

00:45:19.950 --> 00:45:21.250
I hang up the phone.

00:45:21.250 --> 00:45:22.840
Fifteen minutes later,
oh, hey Mario, listen man,

00:45:22.840 --> 00:45:25.260 position:56%
we're calling from the Village
Gate, hey we'd love to have you come

00:45:25.260 --> 00:45:27.640
down and play a gig for us.

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:29.790
We got Dizzy, Dizzy's
going to do it,

00:45:29.790 --> 00:45:31.090
and you know, that would be nice.

00:45:31.090 --> 00:45:32.390
Are you available?

00:45:32.390 --> 00:45:37.150
I said, yeah, yeah,
yeah, I can make that.

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:41.830
Boom, back to life,
Machito Orchestra.

00:45:41.830 --> 00:45:43.140
Incredible.

00:45:43.140 --> 00:45:46.940
Then he calls me back, tells
me yo, the gig went well, nice.

00:45:46.940 --> 00:45:48.240
I liked it.

00:45:48.240 --> 00:45:52.430
Let's go to Chicago to
do the Jazz Festival.

00:45:52.430 --> 00:45:59.900 position:56%
I've got Johnny Griffin, Art Blakey,
George Duvivier, Randy Weston,

00:45:59.900 --> 00:46:05.310
Melba Liston on the band,
I want you to accompany me.

00:46:05.310 --> 00:46:07.930
Well then, well and
the rest is history.

00:46:07.930 --> 00:46:09.360
I'm here.

00:46:09.360 --> 00:46:11.410
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: And
then he helped you break

00:46:11.410 --> 00:46:14.100
into the European market
in a big way.

00:46:14.100 --> 00:46:17.480
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: We had
never tapped that market.

00:46:17.480 --> 00:46:19.880
So we were fresh as a daisy.

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:24.620
So when we go to Europe the first
time, in 75 we played in Paris

00:46:24.620 --> 00:46:30.360
and we played in Berlin, they,
they knew us, we didn't know them.

00:46:30.360 --> 00:46:31.660
And that was incredible.

00:46:31.660 --> 00:46:41.190
Then we went to Europe one summer,
we played 55 concerts in 66 days.

00:46:41.190 --> 00:46:45.470
We covered 13 countries
and 35 cities.

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:52.700
We traveled by bus, plane,
train, ferry, 10,000 miles.

00:46:52.700 --> 00:46:54.150
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum:
That's how you do it.

00:46:54.150 --> 00:46:56.420
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: You know?

00:46:56.420 --> 00:46:57.910
That's how you do it.

00:46:57.910 --> 00:46:59.430
And that's how we did it.

00:46:59.430 --> 00:47:03.500
And at the front of the bus,
and at the front of the train,

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:06.150
and the plane, the
ferry, the bicycle

00:47:06.150 --> 00:47:10.470
and the roller skates, was Machito.

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:15.750
Because, even though he was an old
lion, old lions still have a couple

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:19.200
of teeth and they can roar.

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:22.310
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Speaking
of which, you mentioned earlier

00:47:22.310 --> 00:47:25.790
