tough guy, Mario Bauza.

00:47:25.790 --> 00:47:27.090
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Good cop, bad cop.

00:47:27.090 --> 00:47:28.390
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Yeah.

00:47:28.390 --> 00:47:30.210
So tell me about your
father's personality,

00:47:30.210 --> 00:47:34.480
not just as a family or, but
just what he's like as a person.

00:47:34.480 --> 00:47:37.660
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Well, as far as
music was concerned, you know,

00:47:37.660 --> 00:47:42.070
Machito had his own Holy
Trinity, which was Mario Bauza,

00:47:42.070 --> 00:47:44.120
Chico O'Farill, Rene Hernandez.

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:45.670
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Those
are the three arrangers he.

00:47:45.670 --> 00:47:51.230
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: He put his
undying faith in what they said.

00:47:51.230 --> 00:48:00.010
But, every now and then he would
say no, this is the way I want it,

00:48:00.010 --> 00:48:01.790
and then that's the way it was.

00:48:01.790 --> 00:48:06.950
But 99% of the time, all
decisions were made by Mario.

00:48:06.950 --> 00:48:12.010
One of the ones that Daddy
made, which was a biggie,

00:48:12.010 --> 00:48:16.700
was when the boogaloo came,
boogaloo, Machito playing boogaloo?

00:48:16.700 --> 00:48:18.100
You've got to be kidding me.

00:48:18.100 --> 00:48:19.790
You know? That's for the kids.

00:48:19.790 --> 00:48:25.280
You know, Joe Bataan, Willie Colon,
Hector Lavoe and Orchestra D.J.,

00:48:25.280 --> 00:48:28.200
the LaBron Brothers, you know,
that's what was happening.

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:31.590
As a matter of fact, my brother
in law used to book those bands

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:35.210
to throw dances in Harlem.

00:48:35.210 --> 00:48:40.540
But they came to Daddy, Manny and
George [inaudible] Morris Levy,

00:48:40.540 --> 00:48:43.540
those kind of guys, says
Machito, you know what Machito,

00:48:43.540 --> 00:48:47.510
you're out of style Machito.

00:48:47.510 --> 00:48:48.810
Nobody knows you, Machito.

00:48:48.810 --> 00:48:50.110
You're done.

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:51.410
You're done.

00:48:51.410 --> 00:48:54.760
You know what you got to do
Machito, to come back to life?

00:48:54.760 --> 00:48:57.990 position:56%
So Daddy says, yeah, George, what do
I have to do to come back to life?

00:48:57.990 --> 00:49:00.320
He says, why don't
you do a boogaloo?

00:49:00.320 --> 00:49:02.060
What's what's happening now.

00:49:02.060 --> 00:49:04.160
All these kids, it's the boogaloo.

00:49:04.160 --> 00:49:05.460
They don't know anything else.

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:06.760
They don't know Machito.

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:10.190
Maybe their grandparents, but
they don't know who, you know?

00:49:10.190 --> 00:49:14.250
He says I got a kid on my
label named Joey Pastrana,

00:49:14.250 --> 00:49:18.750 position:56%
he's hot as a pistol, driving around
in a brand new Lincoln Continental.

00:49:18.750 --> 00:49:23.510
Let me get him together with you
for him to write something for you.

00:49:23.510 --> 00:49:27.530 position:56%
Now can you imagine, selling a 50
something year old man that's been a

00:49:27.530 --> 00:49:31.220
superstar, that an 18 year old
kid is going to write for you?

00:49:31.220 --> 00:49:33.740
I mean, that's pretty crazy.

00:49:33.740 --> 00:49:36.140
But he comes to Daddy and says,
Machito, you know what Machito,

00:49:36.140 --> 00:49:39.210
I got a boogaloo for you, man.

00:49:39.210 --> 00:49:40.510
He said, yeah, Joey?

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:41.810
How does it go?

00:49:41.810 --> 00:49:43.610
He says,

00:49:43.610 --> 00:49:48.240
[ Singing ]

00:49:48.240 --> 00:49:55.250
So Daddy's looking at
him, and he's like, but,

00:49:55.250 --> 00:49:58.540
he said, you know what Joey?

00:49:58.540 --> 00:50:02.390
Yeah. I like that tune.

00:50:02.390 --> 00:50:05.670
Let's record that.

00:50:05.670 --> 00:50:08.260
Mega hit. Mega hit.

00:50:08.260 --> 00:50:11.920
Well, we moved to the
Bronx, well after all,

00:50:11.920 --> 00:50:13.750
we moved from East
Harlem to the Bronx.

00:50:13.750 --> 00:50:15.600
So the hot seat's the hot seat.

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:20.000
Oh, to the Bronx, that
was big you know?

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:28.350 position:56%
Oh, yeah. So, I mean, he had moments
when, when his decisions were right

00:50:28.350 --> 00:50:30.430
on the money, incredible.

00:50:30.430 --> 00:50:34.110
I don't know how he did
it, but he had a knack

00:50:34.110 --> 00:50:38.240
for picking the right piece
at the right time, you know,

00:50:38.240 --> 00:50:41.370
the pulse of what's going on.

00:50:41.370 --> 00:50:44.340
I don't, unfortunately,
I don't have that.

00:50:44.340 --> 00:50:45.700
But he did.

00:50:45.700 --> 00:50:49.000
You know, he knew when it was
time to whip in to something new.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:54.740
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Let me take
a moment to just say how Mario

00:50:54.740 --> 00:50:57.500
and I first really connected was

00:50:57.500 --> 00:51:01.130
after this performance
at the Kennedy Center.

00:51:01.130 --> 00:51:03.410
I met him at his hotel.

00:51:03.410 --> 00:51:06.770
And I, to this day, I regret
not bringing a tape recorder

00:51:06.770 --> 00:51:09.690
because he told all of
these incredible stories.

00:51:09.690 --> 00:51:16.650
And then that's when I planted
the seed about, you know,

00:51:16.650 --> 00:51:20.570
you have the library,
have you thought of a home

00:51:20.570 --> 00:51:25.960 position:56%
where it might become accessible for
scholarly researchers or musicians?

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:29.700
And so I encouraged
him to think about that

00:51:29.700 --> 00:51:33.150
and said any time you want to
talk about the Library of Congress

00:51:33.150 --> 00:51:36.590
as a home for that, let's talk.

00:51:36.590 --> 00:51:44.180
Well, I was blown away by the
fact that he then goes and reaches

00:51:44.180 --> 00:51:49.880
into his bag and he pulls out
this arrangements of Tonga.

00:51:49.880 --> 00:51:54.690
It's arranged by Rene
Hernandez, it's in his hand.

00:51:54.690 --> 00:51:59.410
This is one of the great signature
pieces by Machito, and he gives it

00:51:59.410 --> 00:52:03.570
to me and says he wants to donate
this to the Library of Congress.

00:52:03.570 --> 00:52:09.190
So I was not expecting that,
I was so grateful on behalf

00:52:09.190 --> 00:52:12.110
of the Library, because
this is the kind of thing

00:52:12.110 --> 00:52:15.000
that scholars need to see.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:16.890
They come to us all the time.

00:52:16.890 --> 00:52:21.770
And, in fact, there's very
little in any library,

00:52:21.770 --> 00:52:26.240
in any archive anywhere, that
documents this golden age

00:52:26.240 --> 00:52:30.800
of Afro-Cuban or Latin
music and Latin jazz

00:52:30.800 --> 00:52:33.800
in the United States
in the 40s, 50s, 60s.

00:52:33.800 --> 00:52:35.270
You go to all the great libraries,

00:52:35.270 --> 00:52:39.420
there's next to nothing
from this genre.

00:52:39.420 --> 00:52:44.070
And so yes, we're grateful for
this, but we continue to talk,

00:52:44.070 --> 00:52:46.280
and then Mario decided he wants

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:49.960
to give the Library the
whole collection of scores,

00:52:49.960 --> 00:52:53.320
parts and other things to
the Library of Congress.

00:52:53.320 --> 00:52:56.540
Now can you talk a little
bit about why you decided

00:52:56.540 --> 00:52:59.400
on the Library of Congress for it?

00:52:59.400 --> 00:53:04.690
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Well, certainly
and most obviously the Library

00:53:04.690 --> 00:53:09.940
of Congress is the oldest
institution of it's kind

00:53:09.940 --> 00:53:11.360
in the United States of America,

00:53:11.360 --> 00:53:16.690
if I'm not mistaken,
it was founded in 1800.

00:53:16.690 --> 00:53:20.550
There's been two fires here,
I hope there's not a third.

00:53:21.860 --> 00:53:26.470
And some of the most
important scholarly works

00:53:26.470 --> 00:53:28.810
in all areas are here.

00:53:28.810 --> 00:53:36.190 position:56%
Now, most certainly, I had thought
about keeping the music in New York,

00:53:36.190 --> 00:53:41.850
keeping it at home, maybe an
institution of higher learning,

00:53:41.850 --> 00:53:45.550
you know, the Julliard School
of Music or Manhattan School

00:53:45.550 --> 00:53:50.810
of Music, Jazz at Lincoln Center.

00:53:50.810 --> 00:53:53.740
But, I thought you know what?

00:53:53.740 --> 00:54:04.230
No. If you want to be any place,
it is the Library of Congress.

00:54:05.370 --> 00:54:11.510
It took 75 years, but we're here.

00:54:11.510 --> 00:54:19.260
[ Applause ]

00:54:19.260 --> 00:54:20.560
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: This
is the place for it.

00:54:20.560 --> 00:54:24.120
And I know at the time you were
mentioning how important it is

00:54:24.120 --> 00:54:28.830
that not just people in this
generation understand who he was,

00:54:28.830 --> 00:54:33.030
but every generation that follows
will not be able to come here,

00:54:33.030 --> 00:54:37.760
research his music, understand
more about what this man meant,

00:54:37.760 --> 00:54:41.490
what he represented to his
family, to his community

00:54:41.490 --> 00:54:43.780
and to the culture of the world.

00:54:43.780 --> 00:54:47.230
So it's here, it will be preserved,
we encourage everybody to come

00:54:47.230 --> 00:54:49.110
and make use of this collection.

00:54:49.110 --> 00:54:52.320
Because it's not enough to just
put things up on a shelf somewhere,

00:54:52.320 --> 00:54:55.080
this is a living archive,
a living library.

00:54:55.080 --> 00:54:58.970
And to that, on point, I want to
encourage everybody at the end

00:54:58.970 --> 00:55:03.080
of this, we have a display of
materials that Mario brought

00:55:03.080 --> 00:55:05.210
to us that he's donating.

00:55:05.210 --> 00:55:09.320
You'll see these extraordinary
scores, hand written,

00:55:09.320 --> 00:55:14.880
and this is what we are going
to do from now, into the future,

00:55:14.880 --> 00:55:18.030
we are going to provide, we are
going to serve these materials

00:55:18.030 --> 00:55:21.190
in the music division's
reading room,

00:55:21.190 --> 00:55:22.750
the performing art's reading room.

00:55:22.750 --> 00:55:26.420
So it's here, it's safe, it
will be preserved, thank you.

00:55:26.420 --> 00:55:27.720
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Great.

00:55:27.720 --> 00:55:29.020
Thank you.

00:55:29.020 --> 00:55:31.320
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Yes.

00:55:33.820 --> 00:55:35.520
And now I think it
might be appropriate,

00:55:35.520 --> 00:55:39.170
if anybody has any questions for
Mario, this would be a good time

00:55:39.170 --> 00:55:42.010
to ask, and let's begin right here.

00:55:42.010 --> 00:55:43.310
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Yes?

00:55:43.310 --> 00:55:45.610
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Oh, hold on,
we have a microphone for you.

00:55:49.830 --> 00:55:54.100
&gt;&gt; Hi, my name's [Inaudible], and I
wanted to thank you for your time.

