00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:34.300
to record and how she
wanted to record it.

00:56:34.300 --> 00:56:39.210
Gracie came to the band in 1943
when Daddy went to the army.

00:56:39.210 --> 00:56:42.100
So she stayed with us until 75,

00:56:42.100 --> 00:56:47.410
so that's like 32 years,
in Machito Orchestra.

00:56:47.410 --> 00:56:52.300
Like I said, Mario came in
1940, until 75, so 35 years.

00:56:52.300 --> 00:56:58.060 position:56%
So yes, she was very instrumental
and gave the band another character.

00:56:58.060 --> 00:57:02.750
I mean her ballads
are out of this world.

00:57:02.750 --> 00:57:04.470
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: She also
did some great novelty tunes.

00:57:04.470 --> 00:57:05.770
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Oh, of course.

00:57:05.770 --> 00:57:07.880
Very, well Gracie came from an era

00:57:07.880 --> 00:57:10.970
when singers sang everything,
you know, ballad,

00:57:13.310 --> 00:57:17.930
She ran the full gamut
of ability as far

00:57:17.930 --> 00:57:21.250
as what she could do as a singer.

00:57:21.250 --> 00:57:22.550
Incredible.

00:57:22.550 --> 00:57:27.060
I've heard many, haven't heard
any like her, certainly not.

00:57:27.060 --> 00:57:28.360
&gt;&gt; Larry Applebaum: Who
else has a question?

00:57:28.360 --> 00:57:30.900
Yes? Felix.

00:57:30.900 --> 00:57:32.960
&gt;&gt; Hi, Felix Contreras from NPR,

00:57:32.960 --> 00:57:36.200
I've got a million questions,
but I'll only ask one.

00:57:36.200 --> 00:57:38.850
Who were some of his influences,

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:43.060
who were some of Machito's
influences vocal wise?

00:57:43.060 --> 00:57:46.710 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mario Grillo: Well, keep in mind,
Daddy, when he started in Cuba,

00:57:46.710 --> 00:57:49.470
in particular, he had two very
dear friends, Miguelito Valdes,

00:57:49.470 --> 00:57:54.010
and another gentleman
named Panchito Riset.

00:57:54.010 --> 00:57:55.310
They were all the same age.

00:57:55.310 --> 00:57:58.480
They were in a band called La Hora
de Rendtion [assumed spelling].

00:57:58.480 --> 00:58:01.160
Because there was a band,
Rendition, so that they were

00:58:01.160 --> 00:58:03.530
like the kid version of it.

00:58:03.530 --> 00:58:05.940
And, incredibly, you know,

00:58:05.940 --> 00:58:10.920
those very same three guys
stayed friends for 100 years.

00:58:10.920 --> 00:58:15.050
It was Miguelito Valdes that
put Machito [inaudible].

00:58:15.050 --> 00:58:18.470
So, those were his main influences.

00:58:18.470 --> 00:58:23.330 position:56%
Obviously there were other,
Ignacio Pineiro, those type of guys,

00:58:23.330 --> 00:58:29.040
[inaudible] Lopez, different
orchestras in Cuba that he listened

00:58:29.040 --> 00:58:33.390
to and really appreciated,
[inaudible] as an example.

00:58:33.390 --> 00:58:35.860
So his influences were very wide.

00:58:35.860 --> 00:58:41.440
Then he was already listening to
Duke Ellington and Count Basie

00:58:41.440 --> 00:58:44.250
and those orchestras
while he was in Cuba.

00:58:44.250 --> 00:58:49.450
And I'll give you one, one
funny one about Machito

00:58:49.450 --> 00:58:52.490
and his listening habits.

00:58:52.490 --> 00:58:54.800
In the old days, you know, when
you turned on the radio and,

00:58:54.800 --> 00:58:57.650
of course it was a dial
radio, and you know, whatever,

00:58:57.650 --> 00:59:01.550
so when you turned it on you
pretty much could get a gauge

00:59:01.550 --> 00:59:04.720
of that person as to what
they were into by the music

00:59:04.720 --> 00:59:06.450
that they're listening to.

00:59:06.450 --> 00:59:10.180
So we always had station wagons for
all the equipment and everything.

00:59:10.180 --> 00:59:12.040
So I'd tell Daddy, I
got to borrow the wagon.

00:59:12.040 --> 00:59:13.340
I got to do something.

00:59:13.340 --> 00:59:14.640
And he said, okay, cool.

00:59:14.640 --> 00:59:16.500
So I get in the car and
I turn on the radio,

00:59:16.500 --> 00:59:25.060
but it was like a heavy metal,
you know, acid, you know, AC DC,

00:59:25.060 --> 00:59:31.040
Quiet Riot, you know, Metallica,
you know, Twisted Sister, you know,

00:59:31.040 --> 00:59:35.480
and I'm driving, and
I'm like you know what?

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:36.780
That's it.

00:59:36.780 --> 00:59:39.820
Daddy flipped out.

00:59:39.820 --> 00:59:43.280
You know, but, you
know what's this about?

00:59:43.280 --> 00:59:46.360
So I continued on my way and
I get back and go upstairs

00:59:46.360 --> 00:59:48.190
and tell Daddy, here's the keys.

00:59:48.190 --> 00:59:51.200
So I said, Daddy, can
I ask you a question?

00:59:51.200 --> 00:59:52.500
He goes, yeah, what?

00:59:52.500 --> 00:59:55.930
I said, have you lost your mind?

00:59:55.930 --> 00:59:58.730
I mean, what are you
listening to on the radio?

00:59:58.730 --> 01:00:00.240
He goes, what do you mean?

01:00:00.240 --> 01:00:02.930
I said, I turned on the radio and
you're listening to heavy metal,

01:00:02.930 --> 01:00:06.950
you know, speed metal, punk metal?

01:00:06.950 --> 01:00:09.860
What do you, what's
the matter with you?

01:00:09.860 --> 01:00:14.990
He goes, oh no, I was turning the
dial and the disc jockey said,

01:00:14.990 --> 01:00:18.090
this next album sold
five million copies.

01:00:18.090 --> 01:00:24.850
I want to know what are these guys
doing to sell five million records

01:00:24.850 --> 01:00:30.020
when I can't even sell 50 records
in my home borough of the Bronx?

01:00:30.020 --> 01:00:31.320
What is it?

01:00:31.320 --> 01:00:36.230
There has to be something for
somebody to take their 10 bucks

01:00:36.230 --> 01:00:39.870
of hard earned money to
go out and buy a record.

01:00:39.870 --> 01:00:44.420
There's something in there
that appeals to them,

01:00:44.420 --> 01:00:46.620
and I want to know what it is.

01:00:46.620 --> 01:00:52.270
So how does a 75 year old
man listen to heavy metal?

01:00:52.270 --> 01:00:54.980
It doesn't make sense, does it?

01:00:54.980 --> 01:00:57.420
But yes, it does.

01:00:57.420 --> 01:01:00.290
Because you want to know, what
is, what, as we say in the music,

01:01:00.290 --> 01:01:02.990
what's the hook in there?

01:01:02.990 --> 01:01:04.610
Violence? Okay.

01:01:04.610 --> 01:01:06.040
Let's be violent.

01:01:06.040 --> 01:01:08.540
You know? If that's
what it is, let's do it.

01:01:08.540 --> 01:01:14.300
We play an extremely conservative
jazz club, the premiere jazz club

01:01:14.300 --> 01:01:18.530
of the era, Ronnie
Scott's in London,

01:01:18.530 --> 01:01:25.490
Fritz in Soho, right by Piccadilly.

01:01:25.490 --> 01:01:29.400
So Daddy would go out in the
afternoon and watch the punks,

01:01:29.400 --> 01:01:32.440
you know, and then he
would invite them to come

01:01:32.440 --> 01:01:35.620
to Ronnie Scott's to
listen to the band.

01:01:35.620 --> 01:01:40.490
So then Ronnie, himself, would
come and say, Machito, Machito,

01:01:40.490 --> 01:01:44.100
